<;> norm_num [inner, rotM, Matrix.vecHead, Matrix.vecTail, Matrix.cons_val_zero, Matrix.cons_val, Matrix.head_cons]
```

The `<;>` operator is used to apply the tactic to all goals generated by the previous tactic. `field_simp` simplifies expressions involving fields, `ring_nf` normalizes ring expressions, and `norm_num` evaluates numerical expressions.

The key insight is that after expanding the definitions, we get an identity involving inner products and norms that should hold true by the properties of rotation matrices and vector operations. The computational tactics should be able to verify this.
</think>
```lean
import Mathlib

noncomputable
def rotproj_outer_unit (S : ℝ³) (w : ℝ²) (x : ℝ²) : ℝ :=
  ⟪rotM (x 0) (x 1) S, w⟫ / ‖S‖

noncomputable
def GlobalTheoremPrecondition.fu_outer {pbar : Pose} {ε : ℝ} {poly : GoodPoly} (P : ℝ³)
    (pc : GlobalTheoremPrecondition poly pbar ε) : ℝ² → ℝ :=
  fun x => rotproj_outer_unit P pc.w x

theorem GlobalTheoremPrecondition.fu_pose_eq_outer {p pbar : Pose} {ε : ℝ} {poly : GoodPoly} (pc : GlobalTheoremPrecondition poly pbar ε) (P : ℝ³) :
    pc.fu_outer P pbar.outerParams * ‖P‖ = ⟪pc.w, pbar.outer P⟫ := by
  simp [pc.fu_outer, rotproj_outer_unit]
  <;> field_simp [pbar, ‖·‖]
  <;> ring_nf
  <;> norm_num [inner, rotM, Matrix.vecHead, Matrix.vecTail, Matrix.cons_val_zero, Matrix.cons_val, Matrix.head_cons]
```

